hands_on_practices.problem:
An axonal growth cone in the developing Central Nervous System (CNS) navigates a two-dimensional (2D) extracellular landscape, integrating multiple guidance cues via receptor-mediated signaling to bias cytoskeletal polymerization. Consider a simplified biophysical model in which the instantaneous velocity vector $\mathbf{v}$ of the growth cone is proportional to a linear transformation of the net guidance signal vector. Attraction is driven by netrin and repulsion by semaphorin. Each cue produces a signal vector whose magnitude is proportional to receptor occupancy, and whose direction aligns with the local gradient of that cue. Specifically, let the effective signal magnitudes be $S_{N}=\alpha_{N}\frac{C_{N}}{K_{N}+C_{N}}$ for netrin and $S_{S}=\alpha_{S}\frac{C_{S}}{K_{S}+C_{S}}$ for semaphorin, where $\alpha_{N}$ and $\alpha_{S}$ are transduction gains, $C_{N}$ and $C_{S}$ are local ligand concentrations, and $K_{N}$ and $K_{S}$ are dissociation constants. The net guidance signal is the vector sum $S_{N}\,\hat{\mathbf{g}}_{N}-S_{S}\,\hat{\mathbf{g}}_{S}$, where $\hat{\mathbf{g}}_{N}$ and $\hat{\mathbf{g}}_{S}$ are unit vectors in the directions of the netrin and semaphorin gradients, respectively. Cytoskeletal anisotropy of the growth cone is captured by a constant $2\times 2$ matrix $\mathbf{M}$ that maps the net signal into the velocity: $\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{M}\left(S_{N}\,\hat{\mathbf{g}}_{N}-S_{S}\,\hat{\mathbf{g}}_{S}\right)$. Assume overdamped rotational dynamics so that the steady-state heading angle equals the direction of $\mathbf{v}$.

Work in the standard Cartesian basis $(x,y)$ with the heading angle measured from the positive $x$-axis, counterclockwise positive. The following parameters are specified:
- $C_{N}=12\,\mathrm{nM}$, $K_{N}=8\,\mathrm{nM}$, $\alpha_{N}=1.6$;
- $C_{S}=20\,\mathrm{nM}$, $K_{S}=10\,\mathrm{nM}$, $\alpha_{S}=1.2$;
- $\hat{\mathbf{g}}_{N}$ makes an angle $\theta_{N}=30^{\circ}$ with the positive $x$-axis, and $\hat{\mathbf{g}}_{S}$ makes an angle $\theta_{S}=120^{\circ}$ with the positive $x$-axis;
- $\mathbf{M}=\begin{pmatrix}1.0 & 0.2\\ 0.1 & 0.8\end{pmatrix}$.

Starting from the definitions above and first principles of cue integration and receptor occupancy, derive the steady-state heading angle $\phi$ and compute its numerical value. Express the final angle in radians and round your answer to four significant figures. No intermediate "shortcut" formulas are permitted; your derivation must begin from the stated biophysical assumptions and definitions.
